## Key Guidance for Families

**Start here:** Contact ACCESSNebraska to determine which tier (QMB, SLMB, or QI) your loved one qualifies for. The tier depends on income level — QMB is the most restrictive (100% FPL) but offers the most benefits, while QI is the most lenient (up to 135% FPL) but covers only Part B premiums[1][2][7].

**Timing matters:** If applying for QMB, benefits don't start until the first of the month *after* the agency receives all documentation[2]. For SLMB and QI, benefits can go back up to three months, so applying sooner rather than later can recover past costs[2].

**Income limits change annually:** The limits listed above are for 2026 and will change in April 2027[2]. Families should verify current limits each year.

**Asset limits are real:** Unlike some states (Connecticut has no asset limit for QI[5]), Nebraska enforces asset limits[1]. If your loved one has savings above the limit, they may still qualify for QMB if their income is low enough and resources fall within QMB limits[6].

**Hidden benefit:** Qualifying for QI automatically qualifies your loved one for Extra Help with prescription drug costs[3] — this is often overlooked but can provide significant additional savings.

